               <p>ISAAC IZARD. I am a <rs id="t18281204-248-viclabel1315" type="occupation">tailor</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18281204-248-victim2153 t18281204-248-viclabel1315"></join>, and live in Gloucester-street, Queen-square. The prisoner was my <rs id="t18281204-248-deflabel1316" type="occupation">apprentice</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18281204-248-defend2151 t18281204-248-deflabel1316"></join>, and had been with me about fifteen months; I sent for a constable, on the 3d of November, and asked the prisoner in his presence, to deliver up the key of his box - he, with some reluctance gave it up, when I had threatened to break it open; the constable and I drew it from under the work board, and in it were found this piece of cloth, which I particularly identify as mine.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-248-person2154">
                  JOHN 
                  MARDON
               <interp inst="t18281204-248-person2154" type="surname" value="MARDON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-248-person2154" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-248-person2154" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . This is the cloth; I took it out of the box - as we were going to the watch-house, I said it was a great pity to see such a young man taken for robbing his master; he said he was sorry for what was passed, but he could not recall it, and he was ruined.</p>
               <p>The prisoner received a good character.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18281204-248-verdict1317" type="verdictDescription">
